docs.abstract: Workers had accused the companies of unlawful behavior during recent union campaigns.
docs.snippet: Workers had accused the companies of unlawful behavior during recent union campaigns.
docs.lead_paragraph: In a sign that federal labor officials are closely scrutinizing management behavior during union campaigns, the National Labor Relations Board said Friday that it had found merit in accusations that Amazon and Starbucks had violated labor law.

headline.main: Labor regulators find merit in accusations by unions at Amazon and Starbucks.
headline.print_headline: Labor Board Finds Merit In Claims Against Amazon

docs.abstract: Company officials said the terminations were the result of an internal review, while the fired managers saw it as a response to the recent union victory.
docs.snippet: Company officials said the terminations were the result of an internal review, while the fired managers saw it as a response to the recent union victory.
docs.lead_paragraph: After Amazon employees at a massive warehouse on Staten Island scored an upset union victory last month, it turned the union’s leaders into celebrities, sent shock waves through the broader labor movement and prompted politicians around the country to rally behind Amazon workers. Now it also appears to have created fallout within Amazon’s management ranks.

headline.main: Amazon Abruptly Fires Senior Managers Tied to Unionized Warehouse
headline.print_headline: Amazon Managers Fired In Wake of Union Victory

byline.original: By Karen Weise and Noam Scheiber

docs.abstract: Titus Welliver returns as the old-school detective Harry Bosch on Amazon’s Freevee, though he never really went away.
docs.snippet: Titus Welliver returns as the old-school detective Harry Bosch on Amazon’s Freevee, though he never really went away.
docs.lead_paragraph: A show called “Bosch: Legacy” starts this week, and it is labeled Season 1. Fans of the show’s grumpy namesake and his original series can rest easy, though. In everything but name, it’s an eighth season of “Bosch.” They knew better than to mess with Harry.

headline.main: ‘Bosch: Legacy’ Review: More of the Same (Good) Thing
headline.print_headline: Old Beat, But With A New Focus

docs.abstract: Leaving room for disagreement is gracious, not timid.
docs.snippet: Leaving room for disagreement is gracious, not timid.
docs.lead_paragraph: I want to take up a language peeve I hear a lot about: The uptick in (often younger) people prefacing their opinions with “I feel like”: “I feel like it’s a matter of duty,” “I feel like people are ignoring the consequences” and so on.

headline.main: I Think It’s Fine to Say ‘I Feel Like.’ I Reckon Others Do, Too.
headline.print_headline: ‘I Feel Like’ There’s No Problem Here

docs.abstract: Why has the union campaign spread so much further at the coffee chain than at the e-commerce giant?
docs.snippet: Why has the union campaign spread so much further at the coffee chain than at the e-commerce giant?
docs.lead_paragraph: Roughly six weeks after successful union votes at two Buffalo-area Starbucks stores in December, workers had filed paperwork to hold union elections in at least 20 other Starbucks locations nationwide.

headline.main: A Union Blitzed Starbucks. At Amazon, It’s a Slog.
headline.print_headline: Unions Blitz Starbucks, And Struggle At Amazon

docs.abstract: The results were a setback for the upstart Amazon Labor Union, which won a landmark victory last month at a larger Amazon warehouse nearby.
docs.snippet: The results were a setback for the upstart Amazon Labor Union, which won a landmark victory last month at a larger Amazon warehouse nearby.
docs.lead_paragraph: The growing labor organizing efforts at Amazon were dealt a blow on Monday when workers voted by a wide margin to reject joining a union at a warehouse on Staten Island, just weeks after the union won a landmark victory at a larger facility nearby.

headline.main: Amazon Union Loses Vote at Second Staten Island Warehouse
headline.print_headline: Amazon Labor Union Loses Its Vote at a Second Warehouse on Staten Island

docs.abstract: Flush with cash, Facebook, Apple, Amazon, Microsoft and Google are positioned to emerge from a downturn stronger and more powerful. As usual.
docs.snippet: Flush with cash, Facebook, Apple, Amazon, Microsoft and Google are positioned to emerge from a downturn stronger and more powerful. As usual.
docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — Apple, Amazon, Microsoft and the parent companies of Facebook and Google have lost $2.7 trillion in value so far this year, about the annual gross domestic product of Britain.

headline.main: Big Tech Is Getting Clobbered on Wall Street. It’s a Good Time for Them.
